column1: This worthy lymytour, this noble Frere,
He made alwey a maner louryng chiere
column3: He made alwey a maner louring chere°

column1: Upon the Somonour, but for honestee

column1: No vileyns word as yet to hym spak he.
column3: No vileins° word as yet to him spak he.

column1: But atte laste he seyde unto the wyf,
column3: But atte laste he seide unto the Wif,

column1: "Dame," quod he, "God yeve yow right good lyf!
column3: “Dame,” quod he, “God yeve yow right good lif!

column1: Ye han heer touched, also moot I thee,
column3: Ye han heer touched,° also moot I thee,°

column1: But, dame, heere as we ryde by the weye,
column3: But dame, heere as we riden by the weye,

column1: Us nedeth nat to speken but of game,
column3: Us nedeth nat to speken but of game,

column1: And lete auctoritees, on Goddes name,
column3: And lete° auctoritees,° on Goddes name,

column1: To prechyng and to scoles of clergye.

column1: But if it lyke to this compaignye,

column1: Pardee, ye may wel knowe by the name
column3: Pardee,° ye may wel knowe by the name,

column1: That of a somonour may no good be sayd;
column3: That of a somnour may no good be said;

column1: I praye that noon of you be yvele apayd.
column3: I pray that noon of you be ivele apaid.°

column1: A somonour is a rennere up and doun

column1: And is ybet at every townes ende."
column3: And is ybet° at every tounes ende.”

column1: Oure Hoost tho spak, "A, sire, ye sholde be hende

column1: And curteys, as a man of youre estaat;

column3: In compaignie we wol have no debaat.°

column1: Telleth youre tale, and lat the Somonour be."
column3: Telleth your tale, and lat the Somnour be.”

column1: "Nay," quod the Somonour, "lat hym seye to me
column3: ¶“Nay,” quod the Somnour, “lat him sey to me
